'''Dwight Yearwood''' (born May 3, 1959 in Dibe, [[Port of Spain]]) is a [[long-distance runner]] from [[Trinidad and Tobago]], who has completed 30 [[marathon]]s and 33 [[half marathon]]s in spite of his [[disability]], becoming a symbol of hope to many locals.<ref name=Symbol>{{cite web|url= http://www.catholicnews-tt.net/joomla/archives-2009/43-feature/107-fea1101091 |title=Example of faith, symbol of hope|first=Raymond|last=Syms|date=January 11, 2009|publisher=Trinidad and Tobago Catholic News}}</ref>
Yearwood has represented his country in marathons in [[New York Marathon|New York]] (1987, 1988, and 1989) and in [[Barbados]] (1991, 1995).<ref name=Marathon>{{cite web|url= http://legacy.guardian.co.tt/archives/2006-02-07/SA-1.html|title=Born to run|first=Kwame|last=Williams|date=February 1, 2006|publisher=Trinidad Guardian}}</ref> In 2008, Yearwood received a lifetime achievement award, the Alexander B. Chapman Award from Oliver Chapman, the former [[Trinidad and Tobago Olympic Committee]] President watched by President [[George Maxwell Richards]].<ref name=Lifetime>{{cite web|url= http://newsday.co.tt/day/1,25909.html|title=Dwight Yearwood collects Oliver Chapman Award|first=Aslan|last=Mohammed|date=December 31, 2008|publisher=Trinidad Newsday}}</ref>
Yearwood developed [[Polio]] shortly after his birth. The disease left him with a permanent physical disability and a speech impediment. He was placed in the care of his grandmother who became his source of strength and who taught him to do his best to be self-reliant as far as possible. Dwight Yearwood’s inspiring story has been captured in the book, ''Dwight Yearwood – Polio…He survived and conquered'' by Anton LaFond.<ref name=Dwight>{{cite web|url= http://www.guardian.co.tt/sport/2010/12/24/marathoner-yearwood-launches-book-tribute-his-grandmother|title=Marathoner Yearwood launches book|first=Clayton|last=Clarke|date=December 25, 2010|publisher=Trinidad Guardian}}</ref>
