{{ Infobox scientist | name = Susanna Paasonen | image = | image_size = | alt = | caption = | birth_date = {{Birth year and age|1975}} | birth_place = [[Helsinki]] | death_date = | death_place = | residence = [[Helsinki]], [[Finland]] | citizenship = | nationality = [[Finland|Finnish]] | ethnicity = | fields = [[Media Studies]] | workplaces = [[University of Turku]] | alma_mater = [[University of Turku]] | thesis_title = Figures of fantasy: women, cyberdiscourse and the popular internet | thesis_url = https://volter.linneanet.fi/vwebv/briefHoldingsInfo?bibId=922732 | thesis_year = 2002 | doctoral_advisor = | academic_advisors = | doctoral_students = | notable_students = | known_for = Writings on the rise in popularity of [[internet pornography]] | author_abbrev_bot = | author_abbrev_zoo = | influences = | influenced = | awards = | signature = <!--(filename only)--> | signature_alt = | footnotes = }} '''Susanna Paasonen''' (born 1975, Helsinki) is a Finnish feminist scholar. She is a Professor of Media Studies at the [[University of Turku]], and was a visiting scholar at MIT in 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://cmsw.mit.edu/people/visitors-postdoctoral-associates/|title=Visitors and Postdoctoral Associates - MIT Comparative Media Studies/Writing|website=MIT Comparative Media Studies/Writing|language=en-US|access-date=2016-04-13}}</ref> She gained her [[PhD]] from the University of Turku in 2002; her dissertation was on gender and the popularization of the internet,<ref>{{cite thesis|degree= PhD | last = Paasonen | first = Susanna | title = Figures of fantasy: women, cyberdiscourse, and the popular Internet | publisher = [[University of Turku]] | location = Turku | year = 2002 | isbn = 9789512921348 }}</ref> which was later published through [[Peter Lang (publisher)|Peter Lang]].<ref>{{cite book | last = Paasonen | first = Susanna | title = Figures of fantasy: Internet, women, and cyberdiscourse | publisher = Peter Lang | location = New York | year = 2005 | isbn = 9780820476070 }}</ref> After holding positions at the universities of Tampere, Jyväskylä and Helsinki, Paasonen was appointed Professor of Media Studies at the University of Turku on 1 August 2011,<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.utu.fi/en/units/hum/units/media-studies/Pages/Susanna-Paasonen.aspx | title = Profile: Susanna Paasonen, Professor of Media Studies at the University of Turku | accessdate = 7 August 2013 }}</ref> and publishes on internet research, media theory, sexuality, pornography and affect.<ref>{{cite web | last = Paasonen | first = Susanna | title = Home page | url = https://susannapaasonen.org/ | website = susannapaasonen.org/ | via = [[WordPress]] }}</ref>
== Research == On Monday, 4 April 2016, Paasonen gave a lecture at [[Brown University]] in the USA on the politics and culture of online porn.<ref>[https://www.brown.edu/academics/modern-culture-and-media/events-2015-2016</ref> In the essay, "Glimmers of the forbidden fruit: Reminiscing pornography, conceptualizing the archive,"<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Paasonen | first1 = Susanna | last2 = Kyrölä | first2 = Katariina | title = Glimmers of the forbidden fruit: reminiscing pornography, conceptualizing the archive | journal = [[International Journal of Cultural Studies]] | publisher = [[Sage Publications|Sage]] | doi = 10.1177/1367877915580625 | date = April 2015 | url = https://dx.doi.org/10.1177/1367877915580625 | ref = harv | postscript = .}}</ref> written along with Katariina Kyrölä, Paasonen traces the evolution of the "porn stash" from a physical collection to a digital one, and in doing so, examines cyberporn as a site of identity formation. She and Kyrölä suggest that pornography occasions the accumulation of a somatic archive, which are "not merely reservoirs of extra-cognitive sensation but also knowingly curated, reflected upon and reworked: they are simultaneously material and semiotic, intimate and culturally specific, affective and open to representation." In her lecture at Brown, Paasonen suggested that digital pornography must not be understood as something that creeps into society from the outside, but rather as something that already exists in contemporary culture. She writes, "Encounters with pornography therefore become incorporated as carnal capacity-- as what we can imagine our bodies enjoying and being capable of, or not enjoying and being capable of." Paasonen argues, therefore, that interactions with pornography, therefore, can contribute to the development of an individual's sexual identity.
== Awards == The [[Finnish Academy of Science and Letters|Finnish Academy of Science]] awarded her the Jutikkala Prize of €15,000 14 October 2011.<ref>{{cite web | title=Jutikkala Award for Media Studies Professor Susanna Paasonen | url = http://www.hs.fi/kulttuuri/Jutikkala-palkinto+mediatutkimuksen+professori+Susanna+Paasoselle/a1305549365815 | publisher = Helsingin Sanomat (Finnish) | accessdate = 7 August 2013 }}</ref> In the same year Paasonen published the book, ''Carnal Resonance: Affect and Online Pornography'', through MIT Press.<ref>{{cite book | last = Paasonen | first = Susanna | title = Carnal resonance affect and online pornography | publisher = MIT Press | location = Cambridge, Mass | year = 2011 | isbn = 9780262016315 }}</ref>
